<ue5><m0>Chretien won't face assault charges<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>HULL, Que. <m0>(--) Quebec Justice Minister Paul Begin says his department will not allow charges of common assault to proceed against Prime Minister Jean Chretien.<ep>
   ``I have asked for the termination of the procedures [against Chretien],'' Begin told a news conference in Quebec City shortly after a Quebec Court judge said they could go ahead.<ep>
   Kenneth Russell, an unemployed man from Moncton, brought the charges against Chretien, which received the go-ahead after a closed-door session before Quebec Court Judge Pierre Chevalier on Monday.<ep>
   But Begin said he was maintaining a decision his department had already made not to proceed with charges against Chretien arising from the incident last Feb. 15 when he grabbed demonstrator Bill Clennett by the neck.<ep>
   Russell brought no new elements to light in a hearing on his application for charges before the judge, Begin said.<ql>
