<ue5><m0>200 mourn cabby who died in police custody<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>MONTREAL <m1> <m0>(--) Mourners of a cabbie who died 29 months after he was beaten into a coma in police custody were told Monday to forgive the officers because that's what Richard Barnabe would have wanted.<ep>
   But the Rev. Andre Gazaille told the 200 people at Barnabe's funeral that violence should not be tolerated.<ep>
   Barnabe, 41, died of internal bleeding last Thursday night. He was arrested in December 1993 after leading police on a wild car chase when they responded to a broken church window in nearby Laval.<ep>
   He collapsed in police cells and suffered extensive brain damage. He was in a vegetative state when he was admitted to the hospital and never regained consciousness.<ep>
   Four Montreal police officers are appealing their conviction on charges of assault causing bodily harm. A fifth officer was acquitted.<ql>
