<ue5><m0>Stocks rise amid demand for gold bullion<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>TORONTO <m0>(--) Canadian stocks rose for a second session as concern that demand for gold bullion will outstrip supply lifted shares of producing companies, analysts said.<ep>
   Barrick Gold, Placer Dome and Alcan Aluminum led the Toronto Stock Exchange 300 Composite Index up 15.58 points to 5140.10.<ep>
   New York-based investment bank Morgan Stanley & Co. Monday raised its recommendation of the percentage of gold shares that investors should hold in their portfolios to 3 percent from 0, citing tight supply and ``inflation fears,'' said Robert van Doorn, Morgan Stanley gold analyst.<ep>
   ``This is quite bullish for the sector, in that it says that people will really start believing that gold [bullion] will have a major run,'' van Doorn said.<ep>
     The U.S. dollar closed Monday at C$1.3650. The Canadian dollar closed Monday at U.S. 73.26 cents.<ql>
